San Antonio is the second-largest city in Texas and one of the largest cities in the U.S. It’s affordable, economically stable, and culturally fascinating. If you are thinking of building a new home in San Antonio, here’s a breakdown of construction costs. The average cost of building a new home in San Antonio is around $90 to $250 per square foot, depending on the type of construction (excluding the cost of land and site work). The cost is at per with the average Texas rate at  $91 and $134 per square foot. The cost is also within the national average is $100 and $200 per square foot. You can divide the costs of home construction into hard and soft costs. Hard costs include anything related to the physical structure of your house, while soft costs refer to the costs not directly related to the house, such as the cost of land, designs, and permits. Let’s discuss each in detail. Builders in San Antonio focus on the main structure, HVAC systems, and interior details of a home. Here are some cost estimates for the main elements that consume costs during construction. Roofing: Asphalt shingle roofs are standard in San Antonio. The average cost of a shingle roof is $6,815. The price is approximately $3 to $6 per square foot. The costs can go up to $10,000. Electrical work: It costs approximately $10,315 to wire a 1,200 square foot home. This is approximately $8.59 per square foot, including the labor and materials. Also, since you are building a new home, running the wiring through the floors, joists, attic, and basement significantly lower the cost of wiring and materials. It also protects you from tearing down walls in the future for repairs or re-wiring. Plumbing: It costs approximately $4.50 per square foot to install new rough-in plumbing in a new home. Most homeowners spend around $2,280 to $5,120 to install new plumbing systems. The cost increases when you add appliances and fixtures. It costs approximately $12,000 to $20,000 for all installations. Promatcher data also reveals that plumbing contractors charge $64-73 per hour. Usually, plumbers take approximately three to five business days to finish plumbing installation. HVAC: You’ll spend around $11,500 to install an HVAC system. Charges range between $7,000 to $16,000 depending on the size of your home, unit size, ductwork, and additional features. An HVAC system costs $3 to $6 per square foot and the price increases per square foot. Foundation: It costs approximately $5,000 to $20,000 to build the foundation for a 1,000 square foot home. That’s around $50 to $20 per square foot. The costs vary depending on the type of foundation, excavation works and water-proofing. Framing: Homeowners in San Antonio pay approximately $882 to $7,941 to frame their homes. This is approximately $20 per square foot, including labor and materials. Flooring: It costs around $3-$22 per square foot to install flooring (cost includes labor and materials). The average homeowner pays approximately $3,031 for 500 square feet. The average labor cost is $2.3 per square foot but varies depending on the type of flooring. Finishing: The quality of finishes has a considerable impact on the function and beauty of your home. It costs around $90 for builder-grade finishes, $175-$310 for mid-level finishes, and $525-$1,110 for luxury finishes. Additions: You may want additional spaces in your home, such as garages, sunrooms, and extra closet space. It costs approximately $33-$42 for a garage, $72-$102 for a sunroom, and $1,343-$1,470 for a closet. Soft costs are the costs of items not directly related to the construction of your house. They include land, taxes, permits, design fees, legal fees and survey costs. Cost of Land: The average land cost in San Antonio starts at $2 per square foot. Land buyers spend $16,000 to $220,000 to get 6,000 to 8,700 square feet of land. The house occupies around 1,500 square feet of land. Alternatively, you can purchase a plot with a house in San Antonio and pay $6,000 to $13,000 for demolition. Also, if you are buying land in a rural area, be ready to pay more for surveys. In addition, it’s advisable to settle in areas zoned for residential purposes to access utilities easily. Design and Build Team: You need a professional team of architects, contractors, engineers, and interior designers to build your home. Below is a breakdown, based on averages: Permits and Other Costs: The City of San Antonio requires home builders to acquire permits for buildings, electrical, and plumbing works. According to the city website, you can get permits for $60-$27,000, depending on the type and duration of the work. The average cost of building a home in San Antonio is $170. Given that the average size of a single-family home in San Antonio is 2,384 square feet, it would cost you around $405,280 to build a single-family house. Remember, the cost varies depending on the materials, labor, permits, and time. You should also plan for land purchase and preparation costs separately. Generally, it’s better to plan for construction when the costs of materials are low. However, remember to account for price fluctuations in your contracts. Lastly, negotiate construction costs and hire professionals to get the home of your dreams.  